One of our items ordered never made it to the table. Our one maki roll ordered, the avocado was browned in many spots despite it being evident it was recently sliced, the cucumber strips were mushy, and the roll was not well constructed and fell apart immediately. However our nigiri was quite good, some of the slices of fish did get too thick for anyone with textural issues. Gunkan rolls were also decent, though we had to remove much of it due to nori. If we had more time and didn't feel badly about wasting that much food we likely would have brought the errors to staff attention, however once our food was delivered we hardly saw staff so taking action on that was also difficult.

I called the morning my family and i decided to go to Sushi Para II and made a reservation because I had a big party and it was a weekend. We came in a few minutes early to our reservation and still had to wait about 30 mins. Another woman came in and asked for a table of about 7 and the restaurant began building her table before addressing my reservation. The girl’s entire party wasn’t even there when on the other hand my party was. One of my family members made a comment and then the server decided to give us the other girl’s table because they could tell we were confused and irritable.  We were also given a dish that we thought were the shrimp dumplings but was in fact pork gyoza . We also asked the server to make sure and I guess they were confused by what we asked and told us they were shrimp dumplings anyways. It was really frustrating because we asked to make sure and still we met with a dish that we don’t eat because of religious reasons. The sushi para franchise probably sets the standard for AYCE sushi. Their service is typically good and fast, the quality is on the mark and never bad (if you ask me), and the setting is always nice, clean, and casual. Basically, this is your safe choice if you want sushi that isn't going to suck and be a waste of your money. I'm pretty picky with my sushi choices and can be pretty hesitant to try new spots for fear of wasting some decent money on bad sushi/service, which is why I call Sushi Para the safe choice. You can't really go wrong here and the staff tries their best to service you. English doesn't always seems to be the staff's first or native language so there can sometimes be a barrier in communication, but again, they try their best and you can rely on pointing to pictures for help!
